<p>Hugo Ch√°vez, the populist president, is fighting cancer, and the country's prospects hang on the outcome. If he can see out his term to 2013, or win a new one in elections in 2012, a further period of sub-par growth looms as the government spends oil revenue on pet projects and intervenes in all corners of the market. If he succumbs, weak institutions will find it hard to contain the animosity separating his supporters and his enemies, and the contest to fill the vacuum may turn violent.</p>

